---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="Freezing and Boiling Points Across All Temperature Scales" description="Freezing and boiling points across Celsius, Fahrenheit, Kelvin, and Rankine. How each temperature scale was defined." keywords="freezing point, boiling point, temperature scales, celsius fahrenheit kelvin, water temperature, rankine scale, temperature comparison">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Temperature</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="Freezing and Boiling Points Across All Temperature Scales" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 23, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>Water freezes and boils at specific temperatures — but what those numbers look like depends entirely on which scale you use. Here is a comparison across every major temperature scale, plus the history behind how each one was defined.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Four Main Temperature Scales</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-sm font-mono text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400"><strong>Freezing point of water:</strong></p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm font-mono text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">0°C | 32°F | 273.15 K | 491.67°R</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm font-mono text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 mt-3"><strong>Boiling point of water:</strong></p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm font-mono text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">100°C | 212°F | 373.15 K | 671.67°R</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Celsius (Centigrade)</h2>
      <p>Created by Anders Celsius in 1742. Originally, his scale was inverted (100° for freezing, 0° for boiling), but it was reversed after his death. The scale is defined by water: 0° = freezing, 100° = boiling at standard atmospheric pressure.</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Degree size: 1/100 of the range between freezing and boiling</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Used by: nearly every country worldwide</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Best for: everyday life, weather, cooking</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Fahrenheit</h2>
      <p>Created by Daniel Fahrenheit in 1724. He set 0° at the coldest temperature he could create (ice, water, and ammonium chloride mixture), and originally set 96° as body temperature. Water freezing ended up at 32° and boiling at 212°.</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Degree size: 1/180 of the range between freezing and boiling (smaller than Celsius degrees)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Used by: United States, Liberia, Myanmar, some Caribbean nations</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Best for: weather reporting in the US (the 0-100°F range covers most habitable weather)</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Kelvin</h2>
      <p>Proposed by Lord Kelvin (William Thomson) in 1848. Uses the same degree size as Celsius but starts at absolute zero (-273.15°C). There are no negative Kelvin values.</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Degree size: same as Celsius</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Used by: scientists, engineers, physicists worldwide</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Best for: thermodynamics, gas laws, colour temperature</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Rankine</h2>
      <p>Created by William Rankine in 1859. Uses the same degree size as Fahrenheit but starts at absolute zero (-459.67°F). It is the Fahrenheit equivalent of Kelvin.</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Degree size: same as Fahrenheit</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Used by: some US engineering applications (steam tables, HVAC)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>Best for: thermodynamic calculations when working in imperial units</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Conversion Formulas</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>°C to °F: (°C × 9/5) + 32</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>°F to °C: (°F - 32) × 5/9</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>°C to K: °C + 273.15</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>°F to °R: °F + 459.67</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>K to °R: K × 9/5</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>One interesting crossover: -40 is the same in both Celsius and Fahrenheit. It is the only point where the two scales intersect.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/temperature" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Temperature Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/temperature" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
